<paragraph blockId="15.[264,1324,399,1464]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
Discussion: This is the largest and arguably the most striking of Central American 
<taxonomicName box="[264,391,1319,1344]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Paragrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[264,391,1319,1344]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Paragrilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The 
<typeStatus box="[478,579,1318,1344]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">paratype</typeStatus>
is also 
<quantity box="[679,773,1318,1344]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.7" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="6.7">6.7 mm</quantity>
in length and may be a female. It was first thought to be 
<taxonomicName box="[443,563,1359,1384]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Paragrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laevicollis">
<emphasis box="[443,563,1359,1384]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">laevicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but direct comparison with the 
<typeStatus box="[978,1029,1358,1384]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">type</typeStatus>
of that species showed 
<taxonomicName box="[264,354,1399,1424]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Paragrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="azureus">
<emphasis box="[264,354,1399,1424]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">azureus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to be larger, differently colored, the pronotum more heavily punctate, and different in other ways.
</paragraph>
